EXPERIMENT: D7_Z_DR_ATLAS_v1
DATE: 2026-06-06
STATUS: pre-registered
EXTENDS: D6_NULL_NETWORK_TEST_v1 (pre-reg 0f6e33c)
DATASETS: same 6 cancer network JSON files as D6

MOTIVATION:
D6 established that raw delta_r values are not more extreme than degree-matched
random rewirings (H1/H2 denied, 0/6 networks). The null 95th percentile is
2-4x larger than real network values, indicating that the degree-dependent
component dominates raw delta_r variance.

The correct response is NOT to discard delta_r, but to project it onto the
biological residual subspace orthogonal to degree structure:

  z_dr(v) = [delta_r(v) - mean_null(v)] / std_null(v)

where mean_null and std_null are computed per-protein across N=1000 degree-
preserving random rewirings. This is a projection, not a normalization step.
It defines a NEW signal space: degree-conditioned residual control topology.

CRITICAL REQUIREMENT (reviewer-proofing):
D7 must demonstrate robustness across at least TWO structurally different null
model classes. Results that depend on a single null definition cannot survive
peer review ("results depend on null choice" objection).

NULL MODEL TYPE 1 — Maslov-Sneppen edge-swap (same as D6):
  Within each layer, perform 10x|edges| random edge swaps preserving node degree.
  Tests: is delta_r more extreme than degree-matched topology?

NULL MODEL TYPE 2 — Layer-permutation null (NEW):
  Keep Layer A (physical_interaction) topology exactly as-is.
  Keep Layer B (coexpression_cancer) topology exactly as-is.
  Randomly permute the node-to-node mapping in Layer B only.
  (Equivalently: relabel which protein occupies which position in Layer B.)
  This destroys the cross-layer protein identity correspondence (co-hub structure)
  while preserving within-layer topology AND within-layer degree sequence.
  Tests: is z_dr driven by the specific biological pairing of proteins across
  layers, not just by within-layer topology?

These two nulls are structurally distinct:
  Null 1 randomizes TOPOLOGY within each layer (degree preserved)
  Null 2 randomizes LAYER CORRESPONDENCE (within-layer topology preserved)
A protein significant under BOTH nulls is doubly robust.

PRIMARY HYPOTHESIS (H1, CONFIRMATORY):
At least 3/6 cancer networks contain at least one protein with
|z_dr| > 2.0 under BOTH null model types.

This tests whether any biological residual signal survives both degree
correction and layer-correspondence correction.

SECONDARY HYPOTHESIS (H2, CONFIRMATORY):
The sign of z_dr for topology-robust proteins identified in D6
(PTEN >95%, ERK1 >76%, CDKN2A >93%) is the same under both null models.

H2 tests whether sign-stable proteins from D6 remain sign-stable when
using the stronger (layer-permutation) null.

TERTIARY HYPOTHESIS (H3, CONFIRMATORY — MEK1 regime-switch retest):
MEK1 z_dr is significantly positive (z > 0) in ODS-regime cancers
(KRAS-NSCLC, CRC, PDAC, GBM) and significantly negative (z < 0) in
CLASS 6b cancer (BRAF-MEL), under BOTH null model types.

H3 directly re-evaluates the MEK1 regime-switch claim (previously based
on raw delta_r) using the degree-conditioned residual metric.
D6 showed MEK1 sign stability is only 23-30% in ODS networks under Null 1,
flagging it as a "high-variance structural node." H3 tests whether z_dr
resolves this or confirms topology-sensitivity.

EXPLORATORY (H4): mTOR selectivity rule retest
mTOR z_dr is positive (structural damper signal) in KRAS-NSCLC and
negative or near-zero in all other 5 cancer types, under BOTH null models.
(This replicates the mTOR selectivity rule in the corrected signal space.)

EXPLORATORY (H5): SOS1 structural target validity
SOS1 z_dr in EGFR-NSCLC is the most positive z_dr among measured proteins
under at least one null model type.

ANALYSIS:
Script: scripts/d7_z_dr_atlas.py
N = 1000 rewirings per null type per cancer network (2000 total per network)
Per-protein null distributions stored: mean_null1(p), std_null1(p),
  mean_null2(p), std_null2(p) for each protein p in each network
z_dr1(p) = (real_dr(p) - mean_null1(p)) / std_null1(p)
z_dr2(p) = (real_dr(p) - mean_null2(p)) / std_null2(p)
Robustness: protein marked "robust" if same sign and |z| > 1.0 under both
Significance threshold: |z_dr| > 2.0 for "beyond-degree signal"

DECISION RULE:
H1 confirmed → degree-conditioned residual signal exists in cancer networks
H1 denied   → delta_r framework requires fundamental revision beyond z-scoring
H2 confirmed → sign-stable D6 proteins retain their class under layer-permutation
H3 confirmed → MEK1 regime-switch survives degree correction (key atlas claim)
H3 denied   → MEK1 regime-switch is a degree artifact; must be removed from atlas

EXPECTED OUTCOMES:
- PTEN, ERK1, CDKN2A: expected to show |z_dr| > 2.0 under both nulls
  (high sign stability in D6 suggests their structural class is not degree-driven)
- MEK1 in ODS: uncertain (23-30% sign stability in D6); z_dr outcome is the test
- MEK1 in BRAF-MEL: expected z_dr < 0 (71.5% sign stability in D6)
- SOS1: uncertain (54.5% sign stability); z_dr outcome determines its validity
  as top structural target in EGFR-NSCLC

N_REWIRINGS = 1000 (each null type)
RANDOM_SEED = 123 (different from D6's seed=42, ensures independence)
